did.abstract: The Harvey Williams Cushing Papers in the Yale University Library are composed of correspondence, subject files, writings, family papers, artifacts, and writings about Harvey Cushing. The papers document the personal life and professional career of a medical giant and pioneer neurosurgeon. They reveal Cushing as a doctor, teacher, soldier, administrator, bibliophile, and scientist, whose diverse achievements are important to the histories of the Harvard Medical School, Peter Bent Brigham Hospital, and the Yale University Medical School and Library, as well as to the history of brain surgery. arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Part I is composed of 205 boxes (91 linear feet) of papers, while the bound volumes which comprise Part II measure 30 linear feet.
Part I is organized into five series: I. Correspondence. II. Special Files, 1886-1939. III. Writings, 1902-1939. IV. Family Papers, 1745-1940. V. Artifacts, 1889-1930s.
Part II is organized into four series: II. Special Files, 1887-1939. III. Writings, 1898-1940. IV. Family Papers, 1780-1944. VI. Writings of others concerning Cushing, 1910-1988.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Harvey Williams cushing Papers in the Yale University Library are composed of correspondence, subject files, writings, family papers, artifacts, and writings about Harvey cushing. The papers document the personal life and professional career of a medical giant and pioneer neurosurgeon. They reveal Cushing as a doctor, teacher, soldier, administrator, bibliophile, and scientist, whose diverse achievements are important to the histories of the Harvard Medical School, Peter Bent Brigham Hospital, and the Yale University Medical School and Library, as well as to the history of brain surgery.

The papers document Cushing's activities in various professional organizations, his research and writing, particularly on brain tumors and on Sir William Osler, and his book collecting. The papers include a large correspondence with prominent physicians, medical educators and administrators, Cushing's classmates, students, assistants, patients, World War I colleagues, and book dealers, librarians, and book collectors. The papers also relate to the history of the Cushing family, who were early settlers in the Western Reserve of Ohio. Cushing family members served in the Civil War and the family included four generations of physicians.

On his death in 1939 Harvey Williams Cushing left his invaluable historical medical collection of published volumes and unpublished manuscripts to the Yale Medical Library to form, with the libraries of his friends Arnold Klebs and John Fulton, the Yale Medical Historical Library. Along with this library he left his personal and professional papers, family papers, numerous drawings, photographs, and artifacts. The Yale Medical Historical Library issued a short-title catalogue, The Harvey Cushing Collection of Books and Manuscripts (New York: Schuman's, 1943), to describe this vast collection.

Between 1980 and 1989, the Medical Historical Library transferred the bulk of Harvey Cushing's personal, professional and family papers to Manuscripts and Archives. The Medical Historical Library retained the bound volumes of Cushing's personal and professional papers including his diary, as well as published volumes of Cushing's books, biographies of Cushing, and other printed material relating to Cushing.

Each repository treats its Cushing holdings as a complete collection and has catalogued them as such in the Research Libraries Information Network database. For ease of description here, the papers held in Manuscripts and Archives (Manuscript Group Number 160) are designated as Part I, while Part II refers to the papers held in the Medical Historical Library.

A large number of documents in both parts were created on highly acidic wood pulp paper, particularly carbon copies of Cushing's outgoing letters. Over the years these items became embrittled and had to be treated to preserve them from further deterioration. Many items in Part I were photocopied on to preservation paper, while several volumes in Part II received conservation treatment. These items were deacidified and encased in mylar to protect them during handling. Highly acidic newspaper clippings were removed and photocopies on preservation paper were substituted in the volumes.

Through a 1990 grant from the National Endowment for the Humanities to the Research Libraries Group, the Yale University Library microfilmed the holdings of both Manuscripts and Archives and the Medical Historical Library. On the microfilm the holdings of each repository are considered as parts of one bibliographic title called the Harvey Williams Cushing Papers in the Yale University Library. Portions of both Parts I and II are included in the microfilm edition. The microfilm represents yet another attempt to preserve the papers in both parts from further deterioration due to handling.

Series I, CORRESPONDENCE, includes files of incoming and outgoing letters arranged alphabetically by the correspondent's name. Series II, SPECIAL FILES, contains correspondence along with notes, photographs, clippings, and.other types of published material, arranged alphabetically by subject. This series also includes the volumes of Cushing's diaries, scrapbooks, and medical school notebooks, with loose correspondence and other material interleaved. The division of correspondence between Series I and II, between files organized by subject or by correspondent, reflects an arrangement of files developed by Cushing, his staff, and the staff of the Medical Historical Library. Manuscripts and published copies of Cushing's writings: books, published and unpublished papers, lectures, and clinic notes, are arranged in Series III, WRITINGS. Correspondence of family members, not addressed to or from Harvey Cushing, and photographs of and writings by other family members are arranged in Series IV, FAMILY PAPERS. Series V, ARTIFACTS, includes an array of objects which belonged to Harvey Cushing, while Series VI, WRITINGS OF OTHERS CONCERNING CUSHING, is composed of publications which refer to cushing's life andjor work.

The papers include some photographs of Cushing, particularly in the diaries in Part II, Series II. There is, however, no separate series of photographs in the Cushing papers. Additional photographs are held in the Medical Historical Library Portrait Collection. Additional artifacts including furniture and personal memorabilia are also held in the Medical Historical Library. These, however, are not treated as part of the Cushing Papers and have not been described here.

This finding aid includes a listing for all folder and volume titles in both parts of the papers, as the materials appear on the microfilm. A fuller description of the contents and arrangement of each series is included before the folder or volume list for that series.

In the listings for materials in Series I and II of Part I, which comprise the first 104 reels of microfilm, the reader will find cross-references to related materials in Part II. The cross-referencing is to the file folder or general subject level. Individual items are not cross-referenced. For example, the reader will find in the listing for Series I (Part I) under "Welch, William Henry" a direction to "See also: MHL, Series II." This indicates that related material is located in the Cushing Papers in the Medical Historical Library. By referring to the listing for Series II (Part II) under "Welch, William Henry" the reader will find a description of bound volumes of Welch material, as well as the reel number on which this material has been filmed. The listing for Series II (Part I) directs the reader searching "University and hospital appointments" to "See: MHL, Series II." This indicates that no file on this subject is included in the Cushing Papers in the Manuscripts and Archives Department but that there is material on this subject in the papers at the Medical Historical Library. The full descriptive listing of materials in Part II does not contain cross-references to similar materials housed in the Manuscripts and Archives Department. Any cross-reference lacking the designation "Part" or "Series" refers to another series or folder within the same part or series.
Arrangement and description of the microfilm

The arrangement of the papers on the microfilm integrates the materials from the two parts. The papers are arranged such that the matching series from each part are filmed consecutively. For instance, the papers in Series II (Part II), Special Files, follow the papers in Series II (Part I). The listing is annotated with the reel numbers on which materials appear. Reel numbers have only been placed next to the description of the first item on the film, as well as at the top of each page. Where there is a blank space in the column for reel number, the reader should glance up the column to find the appropriate reel number.

Artifacts and published material by others concerning Cushing, Series V (Part I) and Series IV and VI (Part II), are excluded from the microfilm. Additional materials which were not filmed are noted in the column "Reel No." as "Not on film." The designation "Not on film" appears next to the description for each box or volume not filmed, with the exception of those series where the entire series was not filmed. In the listing for these series, there is no column for reel number.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: Harvey Williams Cushing was born in Cleveland, Ohio, on April 9, 1869. He was the youngest of ten children of Henry Kirke and Betsey Maria (Williams) Cushing. Medicine was a family tradition. His father was a professor of obstetrics and gynecology at Western Reserve University. His brother, Edward Fitch, grandfather, and great-grandfather were also physicians. His grandfather, Erastus Cushing, had moved to Cleveland in 1835 from Massachusetts, where the family had become established some two hundred years earlier.

After attending local schools in Cleveland, Cushing was admitted to Yale College, where he was stimulated by his work with Russell H. Chittenden, Yale's first physiological chemist, and developed a serious interest in medicine. After receiving his B.A. degree from Yale in 1891, Cushing entered the Harvard Medical School. In 1895, he graduated A.M. and M.D. cum laude. Drawn to surgery by his work with Maurice H. Richardson, whom he assisted as early as 1892, he spent the year following his graduation as an intern in surgery at the Massachusetts General Hospital in Boston, working under Richardson, John Homans, C. B. Porter, and J. W. Elliot. While still in medical school Cushing had developed, with his classmate E. A. Codman, the "ether charts", on which pulse, respiration, and, subsequently, blood pressure were plotted, enabling the surgeon to gauge the patient's condition throughout the operation.

In the summer of 1896 Cushing became an assistant resident in surgery at the Johns Hopkins Hospital in Baltimore, then under the direction of William Osler and William H. Welch. Cushing served as surgical assistant to William Stewart Halsted. It was Halsted who taught Cushing his slow, meticulous technique.

On the recommendation of Osler and Welch, Cushing spent the year of 1900-1901 abroad. He went first to England, where Osler introduced him to Victor Horsley, the founder of neurosurgery. Cushing decided to go to Bern, where he worked for some six months with the physiologist Hugo Kronecker and with Halsted's friend, the surgeon Theodor Kocher, on problems of intracranial pressure and cerebral circulation. Early in 1901 he went to Italy and, still pursuing his experiments on intracranial pressure, worked for a month in the laboratory of Angelo Mosso, the eminent altitude physiologist. At Pavia he saw the blood-pressure apparatus of Scipione Riva-Rocci and succeeded in obtaining a replica of it which he eventually carried back to the United States, thereby introducing blood pressure determinations into American operating rooms and into American clinical medicine. Upon his return to England, again on Osler's advice, he spent some time with Charles S. Sherrington, at the University of Liverpool. Sherrington at this time was commencing his experiments on the motor cortex of the anthropoids, and Cushing was able to assist in these historic studies. Besides strengthening his inclination toward surgery of the central nervous system, Cushing's year abroad aroused his interest in the history of his profession.

Upon his return to Baltimore in the summer of 1901, Cushing began a general surgical practice and received an appointment in surgery at the Johns Hopkins Hospital. He gradually directed his attention more and more exclusively, first to the surgery of the pituitary gland and later to the many other branches of neurological surgery. Cushing's early operations for brain tumors were disappointing. In February, 1910, however, he successfully removed a tumor from the right parietal hemisphere of General Leonard Wood. This operation, on one of the most influential figures of his time, did much for Cushing's reputation as a neurological surgeon.

Cushing turned down various calls to other medical schools. Hopkins offered unusual opportunities for giving his students training in practical operative surgery at its Hunterian Laboratory of Experimental Medicine, which Cushing helped to establish in 1905. The decision, however, to build the Peter Bent Brigham Hospital in Boston opposite the Harvard Medical School, with close liaison between the two institutions, led Cushing to accept an appointment as surgeon-in-chief of the hospital and professor of surgery in the school, and in September, 1912, he moved to Boston. He took an active part in drawing up specifications for the hospital, both the physical plant and the charter on which it was to operate.

Before his clinic in Boston was fully organized World War I broke out. In January, 1915, Cushing took one of the early volunteer groups from Harvard to work at the Ambulance Américaine at Neuilly, France, for several months. On his return he organized Base Hospital No. 5, a large army medical unit recruited largely from Harvard and the vicinity, which served with the British and later with the American forces until after the Armistice. During the winter of 1917 Cushing operated almost incessantly. He subsequently suffered from an attack of polyneuritis, the results of which were to plague him the rest of his life. On the basis of his experiences he published a classic paper on wartime injuries of the brain.

Upon the death of Sir William Osler, in December, 1919, Lady Osler invited Cushing to write her husband's biography. This task was to take much of his time for the next five years. The Life of Sir William Osler , published in two volumes in 1925, won a Pulitzer Prize.

Some of Cushing's most important publications appeared during the period between 1925 and the time of his formal retirement in 1932. His monograph, A Classification of the Tumors of the Glioma Group , based on work commenced with Percival Bailey in 1922, was published in 1926. In the same year he also published a short monograph, Studies in Intracranial Physiology and Surgery . In 1927, he published a monograph with Leo M. Davidoff on acromegaly. A second volume with Percival Bailey, Tumors Arising from the Blood-Vessels of the Brain (1928), described twenty-nine cases of one of the rarest groups of intracranial tumors. A collection of essays, Consecratio Medici (1928), was followed by two monographs: Intracranial Tumors: Notes upon a Series of Two Thousand Verified Cases with Surgical-Mortality Percentages Pertaining Thereto and Papers Relating to the Pituitary Body, Hypothalamus and Parasympathetic Nervous System .

After his retirement from Harvard, Cushing moved to New Haven to become Sterling Professor of Neurology (1933-1937) and later director of studies in the history of medicine at Yale. He managed to do considerable writing during this period. A condensation of his war diary, From a Surgeon's Journal, 1915-1918 , illustrated by his own photographs and pencil sketches, came out in 1936. In 1938 he published the monograph Meningiomas , in collaboration with his associate Dr. Louise Eisenhardt. A last group of essays, The Medical Career and Other Papers (1940), was in the press at the time of his death. And, by the end of the summer of 1939, he had largely completed the text of his Bio-bibliography of Andreas Vesalius , for which he had been gathering material for over forty years. Finished by various friends, it appeared in 1943.

Cushing bequeathed his extensive collection of rare medical and scientific books to Yale. He also persuaded various friends to give their collections, and in this manner the Medical Historical Library came into existence as a wing of the new Yale Medical Library in June, 1941.

On June 10, 1902, Cushing married Katherine Stone Crowell of Cleveland. They had five children: William, Mary Benedict (who first married Vincent Astor and later married James Fosburgh), Betsey (who first married James Roosevelt, son of President Franklin D. Roosevelt, and later became Mrs. John Hay Whitney), Henry Kirke, and Barbara (whose first marriage was to Stanley Grafton Mortimer and whose second marriage was to William S. Paley, head of the Columbia Broadcasting System). Cushing died at the New Haven Hospital on October 7, 1939.
Excerpted from: Dictionary of American Biography , Volume XXII, Supplement Two (New York: Charles Scribner's Sons, 1958).

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Part I, Series I is composed of most, though not all of Harvey Cushing's incoming and outgoing letters. The series includes exchanges with physicians from around the world, scholars and students of medical history, bibliophiles and librarians, publishers and editors of both medical and popular books and journals, classmates and colleagues from Yale University, Harvard Medical School, and Johns Hopkins University, and family members. While the series includes letters dating from Cushing's student days and early teaching career, the bulk of the letters date from after Cushing's return to the United States following his service in World War I. (Much of Cushing's pre-1920 correspondence is included in the bound volumes in the Medical Historical Library.)

The series is arranged alphabetically by personal or corporate name. The contents of individual files have, for the most part, been left as Cushing and his staff created them. If five or more items of one individual are present in the series, they have been foldered together and listed separately in the folder listing. All other correspondence in the series has been arranged in folders labelled according to alphabetical divisions. Files of unidentified letters are arranged at the end of the series.

The files include correspondence between Cushing and the named correspondent. They may also contain exchanges with the correspondent's spouse or children, letters of inquiry or recommendation concerning the correspondent, and letters concerning memorials or other tributes following the death of the individual. The series, however, does not include all correspondence of the named individual. Correspondence which Cushing kept for reference in subject files will be found in Series II of both Parts I and II. Cross-references direct the researcher to these additional sources.

Transcripts of letters and occasionally notes about letters are present in the files. These seem to have been created by Madeline Stanton (Cushing's secretary and later librarian of the Medical Historical Library) in her work with the files or by John Fulton during his research on his biography of Cushing. Other additions to the files include gifts of original Cushing letters, presented by the recipients, to the Cushing Papers.

The correspondence documents all phases of Cushing's professional career. The earliest materials in the series are Cushing's exchanges with his parents Betsey Maria Williams and Henry Kirke Cushing. More of Cushing's frequent letters to his parents have survived than those from his parents to him. These letters, from New Haven, Cambridge, and Baltimore, record Cushing's undergraduate studies at Yale, his Harvard Medical School training, his early travels and study in Europe, and his years at Johns Hopkins University. The letters include Cushing's characteristic illustrations. Letters Cushing wrote to his future wife, Katherine Stone Crowell, also document his early professional training and practice, as well as experiences in Europe during World War I. Though there are letters from Cushing's teachers such as William Halsted, Sir William Osler, and Theodor Kocher, they are written to him as a colleague and not as a student.

The bulk of the correspondence in Series I, however, dates from after Cushing's move to Boston. Though Cushing joined the staff of the Harvard Medical School and the Peter Bent Brigham Hospital in 1913, he very soon thereafter became involved with efforts to organize medical teams for service in World War I. The correspondence of this period is bound with the volumes of his diary for the period, stored in the Medical Historical Library. Some files, such as those for Boston associates Henry Christian, W. T. Councilman, John Homans, Walter Cannon, and David Edsall, do contain references to Cushing's work at the the Peter Bent Brigham Hospital and at Harvard University, but much more of this is included in the special files in Series II.

The files dating from after Cushing's return in 1919 are voluminous. There are numerous files for professional organizations such as the American College of Surgeons, the American Medical Association, the American Neurological Association, the American Surgical Association, the Association for the Study of Internal Secretions, the Congress of American Physicians and Surgeons, the National Academy of Sciences, the Society for Clinical Surgery, and the Society of Neurological Surgeons. Cushing served as president or board member of many of these organizations. The files document Cushing's involvement and concern over issues such as the purpose of such organizations, their publication decisions, professional standards, the training and accreditation of medical specialists, and the content of professional meetings.

Cushing's own medical research is discussed in correspondence with colleagues such as Percival Bailey, Hugh Cairns, and Louise Eisenhardt. Cushing's medical publications are the subject of correspondence with editors and publishers such as W. W. Keen, Morris Fishbein, and Charles Thomas. Much additional correspondence on Cushing's research and medical publications is included in Series II, filed under the name of the publication or under the heading "Medical Publications of Dr. Cushing."

Cushing's interests in the history of medicine and his book collecting in this field are the subjects of numerous letters. His correspondents include librarians and curators as well as fellow bibliophiles such as Maude Abbott, John Fulton, Fielding Garrison, Arnold Klebs, Leonard Mackall, Sir Charles Sherrington, Edward Streeter, Henry Viets, and William Henry Welch. Correspondents specifically involved in Cushing's research for his biography of Sir William Osler include William Francis, Archibald Malloch, Lady Grace Osler, and Sir Edward Sharpey-Schafer, though most correspondence on this work is filed in Series II.

The correspondence reflects Cushing's association with medical colleagues around the United States and abroad. These include George Crile, Eliot Cutler, Adolph Hanson, Henry Barton Jacobs, W. G. MacCallum, Charles and William Mayo, James Mumford, Ernest Sachs, William S. Thayer, and Lewis Weed in America, Otfrid Foerster in Norway, Sir D'Arcy Power in England, Clovis Vincent in France, and Wilder Penfield in Canada. Correspondence with Cushing's Austrian protégé Benno Schlesinger concerns the plight of a Jewish physician trying to work under and eventually to flee from Nazi persecution. Correspondence specifically concerned with medical education is included in the files for Abraham and Simon Flexner.

The files also include more personal correspondence concerning Cushing's finances, insurance, and family affairs. There are files for Cushing's children, as well as correspondence with Franklin D. Roosevelt concerning the marriage of Cushing's daughter to Roosevelt's son. Exchanges with Lucien Pye and various members of the Williams and Cushing family concern the family's role in the history of Cleveland, Ohio and the Western Reserve. Two of Cushing's patients became his personal friends, and there are correspondence files for the explorer Sven Hedin and General Leonard Wood, which reflect this continuing relationship. Cushing's long-term friendship with his college friend Grosvenor Atterbury, whom Cushing picked to design the Yale Medical Library, is also documented in this series.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This folder contains the correspondence of two individuals named Arthur W. Meyer. One, Arthur William Meyer (1873-1966), was professor and head of the department of anatomy at Stanford University. Cushing addresses him as "Meyer". The second is Arthur Woldemar Meyer (1885-1933), a surgeon in Berlin, Germany. He was the son of Hans Horst Meyer, an old friend of Cushing, and correspondence to him is more informally addressed to "Arthur".

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series is composed of correspondence, notes, printed material, and various other types of material, which are arranged by subject. This arrangement, created by Cushing and his staff, includes voluminous files for general topics, major themes, or long-term areas of endeavor in Cushing's career as well as smaller files documenting a specific event or concern. The files are arranged alphabetically.

Among the largest files in the series are those for the Harvard Medical School and for the Peter Bent Brigham Hospital. These files are similar in nature, dating from the same years and documenting all phases of Cushing's work at these institutions. There is much administrative correspondence including exchanges with deans, board members, and staff, as well as correspondence with and about those with whom Cushing was associated. The latter includes letters concerning appointments and recommendations for students, employees, and visiting colleagues.

Similarly large files document Cushing's publications and speeches. For any particular title, the files contain correspondence concerning research and exchanges with publishers, though not the drafts and completed manuscripts, which are included in Series III. The files for The Life of Sir William Osler and Meningiomas are particularly voluminous. Under the folder heading "Medical Publications of Dr. Cushing," one will find smaller quantities of material concerning Cushing's articles. These files are divided by time periods. Materials concerning articles published in these time periods are arranged alphabetically by title.

The series includes records of Cushing's patients through the files on "Patient accounts" as well as in the microfilm of the brain tumor registry. Cushing transferred the registry to Yale when he moved to New Haven, where he and his successors continued to add data on patients to it as they followed their cases. The microfilm captures the registry as it appeared in the 1930s.

While the subject files in Part I have relatively less material on Cushing's service during World War I than the volumes in Part II, there are a number of folders concerning the American Ambulance Hospital in Paris and Base Hospital No. 5. These include Cushing's post-war correspondence with certain members of his unit and files on the treatment of gunshot wounds to the head.

Cushing's involvement in the Committee on Economic Security is reflected in this series, as is his role on the Emergency Committee in Aid of Displaced Foreign Physicians. This series also documents Cushing's book collecting activities. While the Medical Historical Library holds the books from Cushing's library, this series chronicles how that library came into being. The files contain correspondence with rare book dealers and publishers both in the United States and in Europe, as well as advertising, lists, orders, invoices, and paid bills.

The section Unpublished includes drafts for unpublished works, as well as notes for lectures. These materials are arranged in chronological order, with undated items appearing at the end of the section.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series is composed of papers, including correspondence, financial records, writings, diaries, photographs, and memorabilia, which reflect the lives of four generations of Cushing family members. The series includes no professional material either written by or addressed to Harvey Cushing. Correspondence exchanged between family members and Harvey Cushing is in Series I.

The papers are organized according to the family member who either created them or held them as part of their personal papers. Files are arranged alphabetically by the names of these family members. The lives of family members in Massachusetts and Ohio are documented in these files as is the practice of medicine throughout the nineteenth century.

The series begins with a few folders of material relating to the Cushing family in general. These are followed by genealogical tables of the Cushing family, which were Harvey Cushing for his children.

Files for Betsey Maria Williams Cushing and Henry Kirke Cushing are among the largest in the series. These contain an exchange of letters between husband and wife during the Civil War, as well as diaries of Henry Kirke Cushing. The series also includes several folders of correspondence belonging to Katherine Crowell Cushing. The oldest materials in the series are financial accounts of David and John Cushing, which date from the late eighteenth century.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series is composed of material arranged by subject and collected in bound volumes. The volumes are arranged alphabetically by title.

Some of the volumes such as diaries, student notebooks, and scrapbooks were created by Cushing in blank volumes. Other volumes contain collected material, such as correspondence, memorabilia, clippings, photographs, and the like, bound by Cushing or, in a few instances, by John Fulton. In addition the series includes some printed volumes into which Cushing interleaved or tipped-in related correspondence, clippings, and memorabilia.

On the microfilm, the numerous loose items found interleaved throughout the volumes have been filmed following the volume in which they were found. When necessary these items have been annotated with the page number on which the item was found.

The volumes include Cushing's diaries and scrapbooks of his undergraduate years at Yale, travel and medical training in Europe, and surgical service during World War II. There are also a number of volumes which contain Cushing's class notes from courses taken at the Harvard Medical School.

Cushing's diary volumes for World War I contain photographs and correspondence, in addition to the daily narrative entries. The correspondence has not been analyzed for correspondents, but the chronologically arranged letters fill in the apparent gap for the years 1915-1918 in Series I (Part I) CORRESPONDENCE. The series also includes individual volumes containing collected letters, manuscripts, and reminiscences of Charles William Eliot, Fielding Garrison, William Stewart Halsted, Henry Lee Higginson, Arnold Klebs, Silas Weir Mitchell, Simon Newcomb, Sir William Osler, James Ford Rhodes, Sir Charles Scott Sherrington, William Henry Welch, and Leonard Wood.

Through other volumes of collected correspondence and reviews on From a Surgeon's Journal , The Life of Sir William Osler , and "Western Reserve Medical Traditions," Cushing's role as an historian and author is portrayed. Cushing, the surgeon and professor of medicine, is documented in the volumes "Johns Hopkins medical records" and "Peter Bent Brigham Hospital cases," and in the volume "Full Time," which concerns the question of the appropriateness of medical school faculty having private medical practices. Records of Cushing's calls from several institutions to various teaching positions are in the volume on University and Hospital Appointments.

In the list that follows, all materials found on the shelves in the Medical Historical Library are included. The microfilm, however, does not include the duplicate copies of materials and readily available published works held by the Medical Historical Library.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series is composed of the published volumes of Cushing's books, volumes of collected printed and reprinted copies of Cushing's articles, and additional loose copies of articles by Cushing. The writings are arranged as they appear in A Bibliography of Writings of Harvey Cushing , with books and monographs listed first followed by copies of Cushing's addresses, papers, and reports.

Each title is identified with the same number as appears in the bibliography. The listing here does not include the complete bibliographic citation, but a copy of the bibliography is included in the papers and on reel 126 of the microfilm. Not all books and monographs in the bibliography are included in the papers; most of the missing volumes represent different printings of a title for which at least one version is already present on the shelves.

Some books and monographs included in the papers are Cushing's personal copies and contain his annotations and items of related correspondence and printed material tipped in. In the microfilm edition, only volumes bearing significant annotations were filmed in their entirety. In other cases only the unique material in the volume has been filmed. Volumes which contain no annotations or only Cushing's corrections and emendations have not been filmed. These have been noted in the series listing as "Not on film."

Volumes containing Cushing's addresses, papers, and reports are arranged following the books and monographs. The spine title on these volumes is "Reprints," but the term "reprint" is misleading. For any particular title the volumes may include the work as it was first published, a reprint from this publication, the title as it was reissued elsewhere, or a reprint from the reissue, but the volumes include only one version of any title. Each volume includes a table of contents listing the titles as they appear in the volume. The arrangement is chronological. These volumes have been filmed in their entirety, including text and all tipped in and interleaved items.

In some instances the table of contents will include a title but note that it was not bound into the volume, possibly for reasons of size. Since the Cushing Papers do include copies of these writings, these texts have been inserted on the microfilm where they would appear had they been bound into the volume.

Because Cushing's writings were frequently reprinted or reissued after the initial publication, the papers include a number of these additional copies, which are shelved and listed separate from the "Reprints" volumes. They appear in the listing at the end of the series under the heading: Additional printed copies of Cushing's writings. They are arranged numerically according to A Bibliography of Writings of Harvey Cushing . The microfilm of the series includes only those additional copies which contain original correspondence, other unique material, or significant annotations. In most cases only the additional material, not the text, has been filmed. This material is targeted "From additional copy" and appears on the film after the text copy from the "Reprints" volume.
